(110, 8, 8, 'Blood donation drives organized across cities', '<h2>ü©∏ Heroes Without Capes: Mass Blood Donation Success</h2><p><strong>Voluntary blood donation campaigns</strong> conducted in multiple cities have <em>successfully collected thousands of units</em> to <u>replenish blood bank reserves</u>.</p><h3>Campaign Success:</h3><h4>Collection Statistics:</h4><ul><li>‚ù§Ô∏è <strong>Units Collected:</strong> 50,000+ units in one week</li><li><strong>Donors:</strong> 45,000 voluntary donors</li><li><strong>Cities Covered:</strong> 30 major cities</li><li><strong>Repeat Donors:</strong> 35% had donated before</li></ul><h4>Organized Venues:</h4><p>Drives held at <em>accessible locations</em>:</p><ol><li><strong>Schools & Colleges:</strong> Student participation drives</li><li><strong>Corporate Offices:</strong> Employee donation camps</li><li><strong>Community Centers:</strong> Neighborhood campaigns</li><li><strong>Religious Places:</strong> Temple, mosque, church drives</li><li><strong>Shopping Malls:</strong> Public awareness camps</li></ol><h3>Blood Banking:</h3><h4>Critical Need:</h4><ul><li>üíâ <strong>Emergency Surgeries:</strong> Accident victims need blood</li><li><strong>Cancer Patients:</strong> Chemotherapy requires transfusions</li><li><strong>Thalassemia:</strong> Regular blood needs</li><li><strong>Maternal Health:</strong> Childbirth complications</li></ul><h4>Blood Group Distribution:</h4><p><strong>Universal needs</strong> across blood types:</p><ul><li><strong>O Positive:</strong> Most common (35% donors)</li><li><strong>B Positive:</strong> Second most (30%)</li><li><strong>A Positive:</strong> Common type (25%)</li><li><strong>Rare Groups:</strong> AB negative, O negative critical</li></ul><h3>Donor Experience:</h3><h4>Why People Donate:</h4><blockquote>\"Donors emphasized the importance of regular blood donation in saving lives. Healthcare organizations and volunteers coordinated the drives efficiently. The process was smooth, professional, an